Looking at your code, there's an issue with how you're passing the query parameter. The `socket.connect()` method doesn't accept options like that.

Here are the correct ways to pass query parameters with Socket.IO:

## Option 1: Pass query when creating the socket (Recommended)
```javascript
// At the top of your file, modify the socket creation:
const socket = io(BASE_URL, {
    autoConnect: false, // Don't connect automatically
    query: {
        userId: null // Will be set later
    }
});

// Then in your connectSocket function:
connectSocket: () => {
    const {authUser} = get();
    if(!socket.connected && authUser){
        // Update the query before connecting
        socket.io.opts.query = {
            userId: authUser._id
        };
        socket.connect();

        console.log("connecting to socket");
        socket.on("onlineusers",(data)=> {
            console.log(data,"online users");
        });
    }
}
```

## Option 2: Disconnect and reconnect with new query
```javascript
connectSocket: () => {
    const {authUser} = get();
    if(authUser){
        // Disconnect if already connected
        if(socket.connected) {
            socket.disconnect();
        }

        // Reconnect with query
        socket.io.opts.query = {
            userId: authUser._id
        };
        socket.connect();

        console.log("connecting to socket");
        socket.on("onlineusers",(data)=> {
            console.log(data,"online users");
        });
    }
}
```

## Option 3: Create a new socket instance (Alternative approach)
```javascript
// Remove the global socket declaration and create it in the store:
export const useAuthStore = create((set,get)=>({
    socket: null,

    connectSocket: () => {
        const {authUser} = get();
        if(authUser && !get().socket?.connected){
            const newSocket = io(BASE_URL, {
                query: {
                    userId: authUser._id
                }
            });

            set({socket: newSocket});

            newSocket.on("onlineusers",(data)=> {
                console.log(data,"online users");
            });
        }
    },

    disconnectSocket: () => {
        const {socket} = get();
        if(socket?.connected){
            socket.disconnect();
            set({socket: null});
        }
    }
}));
```

**I recommend Option 1** as it's the most efficient - it reuses the same socket connection and just updates the query parameters before connecting.

The key point is that query parameters need to be set on the socket options (`socket.io.opts.query`) before calling `connect()`, not passed as an argument to `connect()`.

